    <header class="project-header">
      <span class="badge">Research RA • Bunge Laboratory</span>
      <h1>Cognitive Performance Pipeline: Processing Behavioral Micro-Data</h1>
    </header>

    <main class="content-wrapper">
      <section class="narrative-section">
        <h2>The Experiment</h2>
        <p>
          At the Bunge Lab, we investigated how the brain processes
          <strong>relational matching</strong>. Participants were shown sets of
          shapes and colors and had to identify patterns. I specifically looked
          at the difference between
          <strong>first-order relations</strong> (e.g., matching shapes based on
          a single shared color) and
          <strong>second-order relations</strong> (integrating two relationships
          to find a match).
        </p>

        <p>
          The second-order tasks are significantly more taxing on cognitive
          control. My goal was to build a pipeline that could ingest raw
          trial-level data from over 100 participants and quantify the
          performance gap between these conditions.
        </p>

        <div class="viz-container">
          <div class="viz-box">
            <img
              src="images/RT-distribution_graph.png"
              alt="Reaction Time Distribution"
            />
            <div class="viz-caption">
              RT density shift: Quantifying the latency gap across tasks.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="viz-box">
            <img
              src="images/Accuracybycondition_graph.png"
              alt="Accuracy Comparison"
            />
            <div class="viz-caption">
              Success rates for 1st vs 2nd-order matching.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="narrative-section">
        <h2>My Decision Process</h2>
        <p>
          Behavioral data is inherently noisy. I approached the engineering
          challenges with a focus on statistical integrity and reproducibility:
        </p>

        <div class="decision-grid">
          <div class="decision-card">
            <h4>Handling Outliers</h4>
            <p>
              I utilized within-participant winsorization rather than simple
              exclusion. By capping extreme reaction times, I reduced the skew
              from non-cognitive delays without sacrificing the trial's accuracy
              data.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-card">
            <h4>Within-Subject Normalization</h4>
            <p>
              To control for individual baseline speeds, I applied z-scoring.
              This allowed me to isolate how much
              <em>each specific participant</em> slowed down as cognitive demand
              scaled.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-card">
            <h4>Data Ingestion Strategy</h4>
            <p>
              I wrote a Python script to automate the concatenation of hundreds
              of PsychoPy CSV logs. This ensured that every trial was merged
              into a unified, tidy dataset regardless of session length.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-card">
            <h4>Statistical Validation</h4>
            <p>
              Because RT data is typically skewed, I performed
              log-transformations. This prepared the data for rigorous paired
              t-tests, ensuring our findings on cognitive load were
              mathematically sound.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="viz-container">
        <div class="viz-box full-width">
          <img
            src="images/RT-patterns_graph.png"
            alt="Participant Trajectories"
          />
          <div class="viz-caption">
            Participant trajectories: The universal upward slope represents the
            0.6s average increase in response time for second-order matching.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <section class="narrative-section">
        <h2>The Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          My analysis confirmed the high cost of cognitive control. The
          second-order condition required significantly more processing
          time—<strong>roughly 0.6 seconds longer</strong> on average.
        </p>
        <p>
          The data revealed a statistically reliable reduction in accuracy as
          complexity increased. Using a paired t-test, I found a significant
          difference in Mean RT ($t = -13.25$, $p < 0.0001$) and Accuracy ($p =
          0.0005$), validating the measurable drop in both speed and success.
        </p>

        <div class="viz-box full-width">
          <img
            src="images/Accuracy-RT_graph.png"
            alt="Statistical Correlation"
          />
          <div class="viz-caption">
            Final summary correlating accuracy and RT across the cohort.
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="results-highlight">
        <h3>Reproducible Research Workflow</h3>
        <p>
          I designed this pipeline to be modular, allowing the laboratory to
          apply these cleaning and visualization methods to future relational
          tasks.
        </p>

        <div class="stats-summary">
